The list_sensors function does not return the latest timestamped value for each sensor. To get the latest timestamped value for each sensor, you would need to call the get_sensor_readings function for each sensor, with the limit parameter set to 1. 

Here is an example of how you could do this:

{"name": "get_sensor_readings", "parameters": {"transformer_id": "T-011", "sensor_id": "load_current_a", "limit": "1"}} 
{"name": "get_sensor_readings", "parameters": {"transformer_id": "T-011", "sensor_id": "oil_temp_c", "limit": "1"}} 
{"name": "get_sensor_readings", "parameters": {"transformer_id": "T-011", "sensor_id": "power_factor", "limit": "1"}} 
{"name": "get_sensor_readings", "parameters": {"transformer_id": "T-011", "sensor_id": "voltage_hv_kv", "limit": "1"}} 
{"name": "get_sensor_readings", "parameters": {"transformer_id": "T-011", "sensor_id": "voltage_lv_kv", "limit": "1"}} 
{"name": "get_sensor_readings", "parameters": {"transformer_id": "T-011", "sensor_id": "winding_temp_top_c", "limit": "1"}} 

Please note that you need to replace the sensor_id in each function call with the actual sensor_id you want to query. 

Also, the get_sensor_readings function returns a list of dicts, so you would need to parse the output to get the latest timestamped value for each sensor. 

